doc.ContractDescription: IGF::OT::IGF: CITRIX NETSCALER ANNUAL MAINTENANCE RENEWAL PERIOD OF PERFORMANCE: JANUARY 31, 2017 TO JANUARY 30, 2018

PIONEERING HARD X-RAY BAND OBSERVATIONS OF YOUNG RADIO SOURCES WITH NUSTAR RADIO OUTFLOWS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIVE GALACTIC NUCLEI (AGN) ARE THOUGHT TO PLAY AN IMPORTANT ROLE IN THE FEEDBACK PROCESS GOVERNING THE CO-EVOLUTION OF GALAXIES AND SUPERMASSIVE BLACK HOLES. HOWEVER, PHYSICAL CONDITIONS LEADING TO TRIGGERING SUCH OUTFLOWS ARE NOT WELL STUDIED BECAUSE MOST OF THE OBSERVED RADIO STRUCTURES ARE OLD. TO DATE THERE ARE ONLY A FEW DOZEN SOURCES WITH COMPACT (<1 KPC) SYMMETRIC RADIO STRUCTURES (SO-CALLED COMPACT SYMMETRIC OBJECTS; CSOS) FOR WHICH THE AGE HAS BEEN MEASURED USING THE ADVANCE VELOCITY OF THE RADIO HOTSPOTS. THESE AGE MEASUREMENTS IMPLY THAT THE CSO JETS ARE YOUNG (<3000 YEARS OLD). ONLY 16 CSOS WITH KNOWN AGE HAVE BEEN OBSERVED IN SOFT X-RAYS (<10 KEV) AND APPEAR TO BE X-RAY FAINT POSSIBLY DUE TO HIGH INTRINSIC OBSCURATION. HOWEVER, CURRENTLY THERE ARE NO DATA AT ENERGIES>10 KEV NECESSARY TO PERFORM STUDIES OF THE PHYSICAL PROPERTIES OF CSOS AND THEIR ENVIRONMENTS. WE WILL OBSERVED WITH NUSTAR ONE OF THE YOUNGEST AMONG THE KNOWN X-RAY BRIGHTEST CSOS FOR THE PIONEERING OBSERVATIONS AT>10 KEV. THEORETICAL MODELS PREDICT THAT THESE SOURCES SHOULD BE STRONG X-RAY AND GAMMA-RAY EMITTERS. OUR OBSERVATION WILL PROVIDE THE FIRST HIGH QUALITY HARD X-RAY SPECTRUM FOR OQ208 (Z=0.077) AND ALLOW US TO STUDY THE PHYSICAL PROPERTIES OF THE AGN AT THE TIME OF INITIAL EXPANSION OF THE RADIO JET. WE WILL CONSTRAIN THE X-RAY RADIATION MECHANISMS OF YOUNG AGN JETS IN FORMATION, EVALUATE THE IMPACT OF THE YOUNG EXPANDING JETS ON THE ENVIRONMENT OF THE AGN HOST GALAXY, AND ESTABLISH CSOS AS A NEW CLASS OF HARD X-RAY SOURCES DETECTED WITH NUSTAR. THEORETICAL MODELS OF CSO X-RAY EMISSION INCLUDE (I) X-RAY CORONA VISIBLE DIRECTLY OR THROUGH REFLECTION/SCATTERING, (II) THERMAL EMISSION OF THE INTERSTELLAR MEDIUM (ISM) HEATED BY THE EXPANDING JET AND (III) INVERSE COMPTON (IC) SCATTERING OF A NUMBER OF AMBIENT LOW-ENERGY PHOTONS OFF NON-THERMAL ELECTRONS IN RADIO LOBES INFLATED BY THE EXPANDING JET. TO DIFFERENTIATE AMONG THE MODELS WE WILL CONSTRAIN THE X-RAY SLOPES, AND LOOK FOR X-RAY SPECTRAL BREAKS THAT WOULD BE PRESENT IF MULTIPLE X-RAY COMPONENTS FORM THE OBSERVED SPECTRUM. WE WILL CONSTRAIN THE INTRINSIC COLUMN DENSITY IN ORDER TO RECOVER THEIR TRUE NUCLEAR LUMINOSITY, AND ADD TO THE NHI (RADIO) VS. NH (X-RAY) ABSORBERS CORRELATION FOUND FOR CSOS. THE NUSTAR DATA WILL BE ALSO CRUCIAL FOR DERIVING PREDICTIONS ON THE GAMMA-RAY FLUX. IN ADDITION, THESE OBSERVATIONS WILL SIGNIFICANTLY CONTRIBUTE TO OUR ONGOING PROGRAM FOCUSED ON CT CSO. THE UNDERSTANDING OF THE JET FORMATION/RADIATION MECHANISMS AND JET'S IMPACT ON THE HOST GALAXY IS OF PRIMARY IMPORTANCE FOR ESTABLISHING A FULL PICTURE OF THE FEEDBACK PROCESS BETWEEN THE AGN ACTIVITY AND GALAXY EVOLUTION. SUBSTANTIAL AMOUNT OF COLD MATERIAL AVAILABLE TO FUEL THE AGN MUST BE PRESENT IN OQ208 GIVEN ITS COMPTON THICK NATURE. THUS, THE NEWLY FORMED JET MIGHT BE CLEARING ITS WAY BY PUSHING THE ISM AWAY FROM THE CENTRAL BLACK HOLE, AFFECTING THE GALACTIC GAS/DUST DISTRIBUTION. OUR PROPOSED RESEARCH RELIES ON THE UNPRECEDENTED HARD X-RAY BAND CAPABILITIES OF NUSTAR, THE ONLY X-RAY TELESCOPE ABLE TO DETECT OUR TARGET AT ENERGIES>10 KEV. YOUNG RADIO SOURCES ARE LIKELY TO CONSTITUTE A NEW POPULATION OF HARD X-RAY SOURCES BUT THEY HAVE NEVER BEEN OBSERVED ABOVE 10 KEV. IN GENERAL THEY HAVE RELATIVELY LOW X-RAY FLUXES AND COULD NOT BE IDENTIFIED IN PREVIOUS HARD X-RAY SURVEYS. THE PROPOSED TARGET IS THE X-RAY BRIGHTEST AND YOUNGEST OF THE KNOWN CSO AND THEREFORE IS THE MOST SUITABLE FOR THESE PIONEERING OBSERVATIONS. WITH A MODERATE EXPOSURE OF 50 KS WE ARE EXPECTING A SCIENTIFIC OUTCOME WITH FAR REACHING IMPLICATIONS FOR MODELS OF AGN ACTIVITY AND AGN/GALAXY COEVOLUTION. OUR PROJECT IS RELATED TO NASA INTEREST AND SCIENTIFIC GOALS OF THE ASTROPHYSICS RESEARCH PROGRAM TO EXPLORE THE UNIVERSE AND BEYOND.

THANKS TO THE LATEST ACHIEVEMENTS IN THE SUPERCONDUCTING TECHNOLOGY, QUANTUM ANNEALEARS, LIKE THE D-WAVE CHIPS COMMERCIALIZED BY THE D-WAVE SYSTEM INC., ARE NOWADAYS AVAILABLE. FOR THE FIRST TIME SINCE FEYNMAN FORMULATED HIS INNOVATIVE THEORY TO USE QUANTUM MECHANICS TO OUTPERFORM CLASSICAL COMPUTERS IN 1982, SCIENTIFIC COMMUNITY HAS THE POSSIBILITY TO EXPERIMENT THE MOST INTRIGUING IDEAS ON THE NUMERICAL OPTIMIZATION BY QUANTUM COMPUTERS. HOWEVER, DESPITE THE NUMEROUS ADVANCES IN THE ADIABATIC QUANTUM OPTIMIZATION (AQO) THEORY, THE REASON WHY QUANTUM ANNEALERS ARE FASTER THAN ANY CLASSICAL ALGORITHM FOR CERTAIN CLASSES OF PROBLEMS, BUT TERRIBLY SLOWER FOR OTHERS, IS NOT COMPLETELY UNDERSTOOD. THE AIM OF THIS 3-YEARS PROPOSAL IS TO SHOW THE EFFECTIVE SUPERIORITY OF THE AQO BY DEVISING NEW NUMERICAL AND THEORETICAL METHODS, AND COMPARING THEM TO EXPERIMENTAL STUDIES OF QUANTUM ANNEALERS LIKE THE D-WAVE CHIP. FINALLY, AS A CRUCIAL PART OF THE PROPOSAL, WE WANT TO PROPOSE AND INVESTIGATE PROBLEMS OF LARGE INTEREST FOR THE SCIENTIFIC COMMUNITY AND BIG IMPORTANCE TO NASA-RELATED APPLICATIONS THAT CAN BE SOLVED USING D-WAVE CHIPS. FOR THESE PROBLEMS WE ARE CONFIDENT TO OBTAIN A REMARKABLE SPEED-UP USING QUANTUM CHIP WITH RESPECT TO ANY CLASSICAL COMPUTER.
